{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":188997,"duration_api_ms":246253,"num_turns":9,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"cd0d003d-ff22-41cf-8428-8b713f72d6a4","total_cost_usd":0.610507,"usage":{"input_tokens":8,"cache_creation_input_tokens":32695,"cache_read_input_tokens":226180,"output_tokens":4207,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":32695,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":162,"outputTokens":8276,"cacheReadInputTokens":650625,"cacheCreationInputTokens":65003,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.18785825000000003,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":8,"outputTokens":4207,"cacheReadInputTokens":226180,"cacheCreationInputTokens":32695,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.42264875,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Evaluated four amendments against the actual codebase. Two amendments identify real correctness/safety issues (terminal replay missing started_at guard, and merge logic vulnerable to silent field truncation). One amendment proposes a speculative optimization self-described as non-blocking. One amendment conflicts with intentional, well-documented design decisions in the codebase.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-6-7bc10021","decision":"reject","rationale":"The amendment self-describes as 'a low-priority observation, not a blocking issue.' The owned-String approach was a deliberate design choice to unify the serialization and deserialization types (StartJournalDetails / CompletionJournalDetails) so the field set cannot drift between model and adapter layers. Introducing Cow<'a, str> would add lifetime complexity to these structs for a hypothetical future hot-path that does not exist today. The allocation cost of a few small String copies per journal event is negligible. This is a speculative optimization without a demonstrated need."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-bcd2cab6","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a real data integrity bug. The open-match path (fs.rs:3028-3030) explicitly guards runless-to-named backfills with `entries[*index].started_at == started_at` and returns a descriptive error when they don't match (fs.rs:3039-3050). However, the terminal fallback via `unique_terminal_replay_match` (fs.rs:2756-2790) performs no started_at check at all — it only filters on terminal status and run_id presence. This means a replay of a finalized attempt with a mismatched started_at will silently backfill run_id onto the wrong terminal row, violating the disambiguation invariant the open-match path was built to enforce. The fix is straightforward: pass started_at into unique_terminal_replay_match and add the same guard, plus a regression test."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-279a800b","decision":"reject","rationale":"The code explicitly and deliberately skips snapshot-based plan_hash backfill for existing rows, with clear documentation at two locations (fs.rs:2903-2907 and fs.rs:3233-3237). The rationale is sound: persist_plan() can advance snapshot.plan_hash after the original attempt started, so the current snapshot hash may correspond to a newer plan version than what the attempt actually ran under. Stamping it would mislabel the attempt. This is a correctness-preserving design choice — having plan_hash: None (unlabeled) is strictly safer than having a potentially wrong plan_hash. The amendment assumes the snapshot hash is always 'canonical' for the attempt, but the code comments explain exactly why that assumption is unsafe in replay/repair scenarios where the snapshot may have changed between the original event and the repair."},{"amendment_id":"fr-6-926ed414","decision":"accept","rationale":"This is a valid structural maintenance hazard. The merge functions in fs.rs (StartJournalDetails::merge at 2284-2305 and CompletionJournalDetails::merge at 2322-2354) hand-enumerate each optional field for conflict detection and backfill. The shared model structs use #[serde(deny_unknown_fields)] which protects deserialization, but the merge logic has no compile-time or test-time coverage ensuring all fields are handled. If a new optional field is added to the shared structs, the code compiles, round-trip serde tests pass, but append_event_if_missing will silently drop the new field during journal repair — a silent data loss scenario in a repair/recovery codepath where correctness matters most. A merge-coverage test (e.g., round-tripping a struct with all fields populated through merge and verifying none are lost) is low-cost and closes this gap."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"4f9a2db4-40ad-49db-b83e-fca472ede4bd"}
